{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521385"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0,0.86,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104858"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6213"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104858"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man with a history of type 1 diabetes presents to the Emergency Department via ambulance following a witnessed seizure at home. His family reports that he had been complaining of feeling unwell with symptoms of sweating, tremors, and confusion prior to the seizure. The description of the seizure by the family was consistent with a generalised tonic-clonic seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance. On arrival his examination reveals GCS of 15 and he is oriented to time, place, and person. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, temperature 37.8\u00b0C, respiratory rate 14/min and oxygen saturations 97% on room air. A neurological examination is unremarkable apart from complaints of a mild headache.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s seizure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epilepsy","Stroke","Hypoglycaemia","Meningitis","Drug overdose"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this patient\u0027s seizure is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. In patients with diabetes, particularly those on insulin therapy, hypoglycaemia is a well-recognised cause of seizures. The symptoms of sweating, tremors, and confusion are typical of hypoglycaemia and indicate neuroglycopenia, where the brain is deprived of glucose, its primary energy source. It is crucial to always perform a blood glucose on every patient presenting with a seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpilepsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic neurological disorder characterized by recurrent, unprovoked seizures. However, in this context, where there is a clear precipitant (hypoglycaemia) and no history of prior seizures, it would not fulfill the diagnostic criteria for epilepsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStroke\u003C/strong\u003E can cause seizures, particularly in the acute phase, but there are no focal neurological signs to suggest a stroke in this case. Whilst strokes can occur in young people, their incidence is quite low and other causes for his seizure are more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause seizures due to inflammation of the brain\u0027s protective membranes. However, the patient does not exhibit signs of infection such as fever or neck stiffness. Hyperthermia may occur as a result of a seizure likely due to increased heat generation due to excessive muscle activity during a generalised tonic-clonic seizure however a fever in a patient presenting with seizure should lead a clinician to consider an infectious cause such as meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug overdose\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause seizures, but there is no history to suggest recent drug ingestion and the rapid return to baseline does not indicate a likely drug overdose as the cause for this patient\u0027s seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing hypoglycaemia-induced seizures, rapid glucose administration is crucial. If the patient is conscious and able to swallow safely, oral glucose (e.g., glucose gel or sugar-containing drinks) can be given. For unconscious patients or those unable to swallow safely, intravenous dextrose (usually 50% dextrose solution) should be administered immediately. In pre-hospital settings or when intravenous access is challenging, subcutaneous, intramuscular or intranasal glucagon can be used. After initial treatment, the patient\u0027s blood glucose levels should be closely monitored, and the underlying cause of hypoglycaemia should be investigated to prevent recurrence. Long-term management may involve adjusting insulin regimens, educating the patient about hypoglycaemia recognition and prevention, and ensuring they have a glucagon kit for emergency use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe, untreated hypoglycaemia is a potential cause of seizures","Immediate management of hypoglycaemia-induced seizures involves rapid glucose administration"],"references":["Cryer PE. Hypoglycaemia: pathophysiology, diagnosis and treatment. Oxford University Press; 2016.","Seaquist ER. Hypoglycemia and diabetes: a report of a workgroup of the American Diabetes Association and the Endocrine Society. Diabetes Care. 2013 May;36(5):1384-95. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23589542/","Yale JF, Paty B, Senior PA. Hypoglycemia. In: Kahn CR, Weir GC, King GL, Jacobson AM, Moses AC, Smith RJ, editors. Joslin\u0027s Diabetes Mellitus. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health; 2015:911-32.","Pollandt S, Bleck TP. Chapter 45 - Thermoregulation in epilepsy. In: Romanovsky AA, editor. Handbook of Clinical Neurology. 157: Elsevier; 2018. p. 737-47.  Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/B9780444640741000458"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T12:29:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T12:29:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6213"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104858"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":n